node.text:
We talk a lot about salad dressings in the upcoming “cooking at home” (link in bio). This is a super quick and simple dressing …I make endless variations of this. Sub out vinegar with lime juice, add minced garlic, use fish sauce instead of tamari…just know that the ratio of acid to oil should be around 1:3

I think this dressing was a couple glugs of olive oil, 15 shakes of chili flakes and sesame seeds, couple long pours of rice wine vinegar, one pour of @momolongplay sesame oil & tamari, and a big squeeze of agave. 

I used this dressing for a tomato, onion, soft tofu salad.

node.text:
Cooking at home can and should be super simple, and there's ways to free yourself from following recipes. In fact, this recipe isn't even in the book! i just made it on the fly because I had to use three ears of corn that needed to go (not enough for everyone to have their own...otherwise I would've just microwaved the corn on the cob.  Some oyster mushrooms that needed to bet used and a nub of frozen bacon ends). Also if you do shuck corn...this is a good way to do it (there are actually tons of tips for shucking corn but this one works too). More on this in my cookbook coming out soon. Professional cooking techniques, more often than not, don't translate well in a home.

@cookanyday @momolongplay @majordomomedia

I will try and do a video or something with recipes for everything (but maybe this will also never happen because I’m lazy).

node.text: Dinner is ready…Sunday Ssäm: pan fried sliced pork butt/belly….sautéed bean sprouts in the pan drippings, pork fat, roasted mushrooms in dripping, salad from previous post, banchan (fish cake, kimchi fresh and dried radish, pickled 깻잎), ssämjang, momofuku sesame oil with savory salt….wrap it all up in lettuce. I really think this is one of the best ways to eat meat. It’s the original protein style…we go in depth on making this kind of meal in “cooking at home” (link in bio).

node.text:
We talk a lot about salad dressings in the upcoming “cooking at home” (link in bio). This is a super quick and simple dressing …I make endless variations of this. Sub out vinegar with lime juice, add minced garlic, use fish sauce instead of tamari…just know that the ratio of acid to oil should be around 1:3

I think this dressing was a couple glugs of olive oil, 15 shakes of chili flakes and sesame seeds, couple long pours of rice wine vinegar, one pour of @momolongplay sesame oil & tamari, and a big squeeze of agave. 

I used this dressing for a tomato, onion, soft tofu salad.

node.text: Boiled beef part 2: I was going to add garlic and savory salt regardless of the direction so I do that now. Bring salt level pretty close to what I want when the dish is finished…whatever it is going to be. I started it with just water and then nothing else. Once I’m able to start skimming I season my beef. Allows me to walk away and do other things and only come back to add water to the previous levels…so any salt that I add is just to adjust. I’m thinking I will make a classic Korean banchan of jjangjorim, and also some version of a beef stew with thyme and veg etc. we talk about all of this in “cooking at home”.
